2020-06-26 10:25:40-05:00,Global Briefing: EU carbon price projected to average €32 in 2020s,"Plus all the top green business news from around the world this week, including Denmark's new climate law and the Australian mining sector's net zero pledge IETA sets out net zero carbon trading vision The International Emissions Trading Association (IETA) has unveiled its plan to lobby governments, companies and carbon markets to set net zero emissions targets in line with the Paris Agreement's 1.5C global warming ambition, as its members predicted EU prices would average €32 per tonne over the next decade. A key part of the Paris Agreement encourages countries to agree on carbon trading systems in pursuit of climate change goals, and IETA's government council said it would push for governments and organisations to step up their climate ambitions to net zero by the middle of the century. ""IETA's work with governments around the world will emphasise the importance of accelerating work to make the 'net' operational so that 'net zero' is achievable,"" said Dirk Forrister, president and CEO of IETA. ""By this, we mean that policies should enable companies and sectors to cooperate through trading policies, including use of natural climate solutions and a wide range of technological removals."" ""International cooperation through markets will be essential for achieving net zero, because not every country has the same opportunities to reduce or remove greenhouse gases - while others have more opportunities than they need,"" he continued. ""The trading system envisioned in Article 6 [of the Paris Agreement] will bring these opportunities and needs together for mutual benefit of the countries involved - advancing the global goal."" IETA also this week released the results of its annual survey, revealing 71 per cent of its 137 members and 22 IATA (International Air Transport Association) have now set net zero pledges.",BBL,en,BusinessGreen
