2020-02-24 18:01:36-05:00,Europe's biggest firms are putting €124bn towards net zero - but is it enough?,"CDP analysis of more than 800 companies shows corporate green investment is growing, but businesses must now double down to achieve net zero Many of Europe's biggest companies now appear to be recognising both the necessity of the low carbon transition and the opportunities that should arise from deep decarbonisation, as they mobilised capital investment to the tune of €124bn behind clean technologies and R&D initiatives last year. But despite the surge in clean tech-related spending, the scale of green investment these firms are offering at present remains far from the level needed to shield them against transition risks and ensure the world has a reasonable chance of reaching net zero emissions by 2050. That is the stark conclusion of new analysis today from CDP, which argued European companies must double their average share of capital expenditure on low carbon investments from 12 per cent in 2019, to at least 25 per cent in order to be consistent with a 2050 net zero pathway. The investor-backed carbon disclosure non-profit analysed the capital expenditure reported by 882 major European firms in 2019, collectively responsible for more than three quarters - around 3.2 gigatonnes - of the entire continent's total greenhouse gas emissions, as well as 76 per cent of European market capitalisation.",BBL,en,BusinessGreen
